stop comparing healthy toddlers to mentaly ill adults and teenagers. It's not helpful and we already know

Overall healthy toddlers and (typically) teenagers with an eating disorder are very different and other than eating the same they are very hard to compare. Telling someone with an ed that they 'eat like a toddler' doesn't do what you think it does.
A toddler eats about 1200kcals because they need to however someone with an ed eats 1200kcals because they have an ed.
If a teenager ate 1200kcals a day then they would probably lose weight, however they would also have the effects of malnutrition as well as possibly stunting the height.

Toddlers do not want to lose weight or go on a diet, they also do not have a mental illness. Teenagers however DO have a sense of self and have a large understanding of how  themselves and others perceive them. They are also able to make the choice to change their diet.

Toddlers also haven't yet developed a sense of self, this means that they don't see things in the same way that a older person would. They aren't able to see others as this or that they are just them. Toddlers also don't understand weight, or body image

Now why this isn't a fair comparison: 
A toddler is normally very active and  is growing rapidly so requires alot of energy, however a teenager isn't growing as much and isn't typically as active.

This means that they aren't growing as fast or as much as a toddler would be. Alot of this energy going towards puberty, on average a 14 year old needs about 2000kcals. Which is higher that 1200kcals but it is possible for a 14 y/o to have this amount

This is were it becomes very different from someone who has an eating disorder. Most people who develop an eating disorder are in there teenage years (although there is an increaseing amount of people who are older)

This all varies between hight and activity levels, like it would with anyone else. 

However a toddler is constantly growing, learning and developing every day. This means that they need the energy to be able to grow as they should.
